A Bookworm's Guide to Becoming a Better Reader

By Hannah B. 

Let me start this off by saying there aren't really good or bad readers. There are different kinds of readers, sure, but I personally don't think there's a spectrum of good or bad to fall into. So for the sake of this guide, let's just define "good reader" as a healthy, consistent, well-rounded reader. Here are a few tips and stories on how I became a "better" reader over time.

1. Read anything.

And by that I mean keep an open mind. We all have our favorites, but don't be afraid to read new things, new texts—not even just stories. Your favorites aren't going anywhere; you can always go back to them. Enjoy comic book movies but haven't tried reading a comic book? Never (willingly) picked up a science book since you graduated? Try it once. Don't be limited by what you're "supposed" to read. Take the time to explore new genres, even new media. Give audiobooks a shot. If these are for you, then congratulations! If not, there are more fish in the sea—or rather, more books on the shelf.

Must-read lists and award winners are a great resource, but I find that the best algorithm is found in your personal circles. Ask your friends what they're reading, try their favorites, explore their interests. Let their personalities and preferences be your guide to finding your next read.

 

2. Build a habit.

Like most skills, practice is the best and most effective way to improve your reading, at least quantitatively. Pick a time in your day when your brain is most receptive of what you read, and make a habit out of it. For me, it's in the morning before I start working, to get my mind warmed up for the day. So every day, I set aside an hour before work to just sit, read, and have my morning coffee.

Make your own reading routine and stick to it. Not only will it help you read more, it can also help you add structure and consistency to your days.

3. Take breaks.

Now, just because I said read everything, that doesn't mean read 24/7. (Although for some of us, that's the dream, right?) Your brain needs a break, too. If you're reading for leisure, it should give you the time and space to relax, to wind down. It shouldn't add pressure to our already stressful lives. It doesn't matter if you read one or a hundred books a year. If you read, you're a reader.

I read somewhere is to alternate between reading new books and re-reading old ones. That way, you can scratch the reading itch while taking a break from new adventures; just reliving an old story that you already know the ending to.

 

4. Take notes.

Even though reading is relaxing, it's still mental exercise. It's easy—and fun—to get lost in the pages, and most of us read precisely for that reason. But if what you're reading pushes your mind and produces thoughts and emotions you didn't expect, note these down. Hopefully it will help you process what you read, and perhaps also help you discover new things about yourself, too.

I personally like writing directly on my books, so that my train of thought isn't derailed too much—but I know this debate is its own can of worms, so do whatever works for you. Type down your thoughts, record voice notes, write on a separate notebook, fill the pages of your book with sticky notes. There is no right or wrong way to do this; the only important thing is that you actually do it.

 

5.  Don't be afraid to break up with your books.

Listen, if you're keeping an open mind and trying out different kinds of books, chances are you'll encounter a few that, no matter how hard you try, just won't stick with you. And that's okay. You're not going to like every single book you read, so don't be pressured to finish every book you start. What matters is you were open to a new adventure, and you gave it a fair shot. If it really doesn't work out, there's no harm in setting it down and starting something new.

I have my fair share of books that I've given up on. Instead of gathering dust in my bookshelf, I give them to friends who I think might enjoy them. It's like finding them a new home, one where they will be read and appreciated, while also making space in my own shelf for the books I hold close to my heart and new reads waiting to be discovered.

 

6. Talk about what you read.

For me, one of the best parts of reading is sharing what I read with others. There are few things greater than the joy of discovering that the stories you love are loved by others, too. Discussing your reads with fellow readers—or even non-readers—offers you different perspectives and helps you discover things that you perhaps have missed on your own reading.

Join a book club or a community like Bookworm Corner so that you have an avenue to discuss what you've read, gather insights from your fellow readers, and make new friends along the way.

What do you do to become a better reader? Share your tips and stories in the comments!
